Did you tell the photographer how you wanted it done?

Sawada: ‚ÄúI told him I was an artist and wanted to make photographs with him. I told him to think that each weekend new girls would show up to make the OMIAI. I didn‚Äôt want him to think of me as the same girl...‚Äù https://t.co/cFeZcdS945

Sawada: ‚ÄúEvery weekend I went to the hair salon and put on a kimono. Then I went to the photo studio on the street in Japan. I would take a picture and then change my clothes to western dress. Then I would go to the studio again the next weekend.‚Äù https://t.co/kjYcxW9R6a

What was the process of making that work?

Sawada: ‚ÄúI gained 10 pounds before I started taking the pictures, and in six months I lost 40 pounds because I wanted to look different in each photo. I wanted to change the way my legs looked.‚Äù https://t.co/MEs56MBLoc

Sawada: ‚ÄúIf both sides are interested, they can meet for lunch or dinner accompanied by their parents and steps for marriage proceed from there. In the old days, some people chose their marriage partner just through photographs, without even meeting each other.‚Äù https://t.co/YVeTa2CD3x

Tell us about OMIAI, the series that represents a traditional Japanese matchmaking technique.

Sawada: ‚ÄúOMIAI is a tradition that is somehow still working today. Usually, there is a matchmaker and photographs are exchanged before the meeting.‚Äù https://t.co/lFn9GF281Y

What themes are you exploring in your work?

Sawada: ‚ÄúI‚Äôm interested in the relationship between inside and outside. If you wear a sexy dress or if you wear kids‚Äô clothes or casual clothes, people treat you differently. Even though you are you no matter what you wear...‚Äù https://t.co/bcNgIscQdr

When did you start photographing yourself?

Sawada: ‚ÄúI began making self-portraits when I was 19... I can‚Äôt even explain in Japanese why I liked them so much. It was instinctual. It‚Äôs as if I knew that this was going to be my style, that this is what I wanted to do." https://t.co/7DBm2mImpx

The "Michelangelo" exhibition had different goals. 

Michelangelo's drawings are delicate and needed to be shown in low light. To create an intimate experience, we chose dark wall colors that matched the chalk, paper, and gold frames of the drawings. https://t.co/WEW3djgEuu

For the exhibition "Power and Pathos" (2015), we chose blues that would make visitors feel as if they were viewing the bronze sculptures outdoors and in broad daylight. Almost like they were outside in a garden, since this was their original viewing setting. https://t.co/2mGjCOQFYr
We recently repainted a few galleries in the West Pavilion. We chose a Victorian Red, because the artworks in the gallery were meant to be displayed in such a setting. https://t.co/rQaGwSB6Tg

Designers and curators choose wall colors to meet the goals of each project.

1. Robin Hood

Medieval history, both real and legendary, all set to some catchy tunes‚Äîwhat more could you ask for? Robin Hood is one of the most enduring and famous figures from medieval English folklore.

Overall ranking: üè∞üè∞üè∞üè∞üè∞ https://t.co/xWFPWlBlXl

2. The Sword in the Stone

Merlin references the London Times (founded 1785), saying it ‚Äúwon‚Äôt be out for another twelve hundred years.‚Äù Doing the math sets the film around 585. But the aesthetic evokes the High Middle Ages (about 1000‚Äì1300).

Overall ranking: üè∞üè∞üè∞üè∞1/2 https://t.co/Wu4TMgYIJZ

3. Sleeping Beauty

Sleeping Beauty is based on a tale that finds its early origins in a 14th-century romance text, filtered through the 17th-century French author Charles Perrault and, of course, the Brothers Grimm.

Overall ranking: üè∞üè∞üè∞üè∞¬Ω https://t.co/90nOYQVZda

4. Brave

Runic inscriptions, petroglyphs, and a stonehenge connect this fantasy medieval world with art and architecture that one can still explore today in Scotland, England, and elsewhere.

Overall ranking: üè∞üè∞üè∞üè∞ https://t.co/U3Tv4ILeMw

5. The Hunchback of Notre Dame

Set in late 15th-century Paris, there are plenty of medieval places, attitudes, and hierarchy. The Feast of Fools (January 6), around which the tale turns, was observed in France by people before the 16th century.

Overall ranking: üè∞üè∞üè∞¬Ω https://t.co/rhHjdkTfwe

Also 6 (a tie!) Mulan

The story of a girl who disguises herself as a soldier in her father‚Äôs stead can be read in the 31-couplet Ballad of Mulan. Given the brevity of the text, Disney took liberties to expand the content, veering into cultural parody.

Overall ranking: üè∞üè∞üè∞ https://t.co/nQ8CgslRqs

6. Moana

An archaeological look at the film suggests a date range of 1000‚Äì1500, the period when Pacific voyagers began actively sailing to Central and Eastern Polynesia.

Overall ranking: üè∞üè∞üè∞ https://t.co/Pipns3izmQ

7. The Emperor's New Groove

The Inca sovereign, but make him a llama. The Inca ruled the Andean world, which included parts of Peru, Bolivia, Ecuador, and Chile, from about the 1100s until the Spanish conquest of 1572. 

Overall ranking: üè∞üè∞¬Ω https://t.co/5XuNlFfATz

8. Aladdin

Set anywhere from the 4th to the 18th century, Disney‚Äôs culturally problematic retelling of a tale about a guy who gets the girl thanks to magical intervention.

Overall ranking: üè∞üè∞ https://t.co/DyI9JRcL4n

Every character is somehow the worst character in this extremely bizarre attempt at medieval worlding. The story has plenty of medieval fantasy elements, but their combination is just so weird.

Ranking: üè∞1/2 https://t.co/r52xazZMlK
